[49m[38;5;9m- 474     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Behavioral-health-specific handling.** Behavioral-health visits have stricter retention windows, narrower access controls, and per-encounter explicit consent. Some institutions exclude behavioral-health from ambient documentation entirely. The architecture supports a behavioral-health profile that the institution can apply per visit type or per clinician. Recipe 2.8 and recipe 10.6 cover the behavioral-health profile pattern in detail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Behavioral-health-specific handling and 42 CFR Part 2 profile in the in-person setting.** Behavioral-health visits have stricter retention windows, narrower access controls, and per-encounter explicit consent. Some institutions exclude behavioral-health from ambient documentation entirely. The architecture supports a behavioral-health profile that the institution can apply per visit type or per clinician.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The in-person-distinct dimensions of the behavioral-health profile include:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - In-encounter pause-and-resume affordance. Two modes: hard-pause (audio capture stops at the device; no audio is transmitted to the cloud during the pause; the clinician resumes when the sensitive moment has passed) and soft-pause (audio is captured and stored but tagged as off-the-record; the tagged segments are excluded from note generation but retained for the audit trail). The clinician controls pause-and-resume through the in-room device interface; the system logs pause events with timestamps for the audit record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - In-room bystander consent capture for behavioral-health visits. Where 42 CFR Part 2 applies (substance-use disorder treatment records), the system captures explicit Part-2 disclosure acknowledgment from the patient and any bystanders before ambient documentation proceeds. The disclosure specifies the federally-required Part-2 language about re-disclosure restrictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Visit-type-flag-based exclusion enforcement at scheduling time. Behavioral-health visit types that are institutionally excluded from ambient documentation are enforced at scheduling: the ambient feature is not offered for those visit types. A clinician-side override is available for visit types where the institution permits ambient documentation with stricter consent; the override requires the clinician to confirm the stricter consent workflow before the session bootstraps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Per-room device configuration for behavioral-health rooms. Behavioral-health rooms (therapy offices, group rooms, substance-use counseling rooms) have shorter default retention windows (24 hours or immediate-on-signing for audio) and the device configuration reflects this: the device's UI prominently displays the recording status, and the default state is "ambient off" rather than "ambient on" (the clinician must actively enable rather than actively disable).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Per-state regulatory profile. The in-person setting makes the regulatory profile recipe-acute: the clinic's physical location unambiguously determines which state's laws govern, unlike telehealth where the patient's location introduces ambiguity. The institutional compliance team maintains per-state behavioral-health recording consent requirements and feeds them into the consent-regime determination at encounter start.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipe 2.8 covers the LLM-driven note generation and EHR write-back specifics for behavioral-health content. Recipe 10.6 covers the telehealth version of the behavioral-health profile. This recipe's contribution is the in-person-distinct dimensions above.
